Efficient Product Price Lookup

An e-commerce platform maintains a catalog of product prices that is sorted in strictly increasing order. Since the catalog is large, the system must use an efficient search mechanism to quickly locate a product price.

When a customer searches for a specific price:

If the price exists in the catalog, return its index (0-based)
If the price does not exist, return -1

Your task is to implement an efficient algorithm to perform this search.

Input format :
First line: Integer n → number of product prices
Second line: n space-separated integers → sorted product prices
Third line: Integer target → price to search
Output format :
Print the index of the target price
If not found, print -1
Code constraints :
1 ≤ n ≤ 10^4
-10^4 < price, target < 10^4
All values are unique
Prices are sorted in increasing order
Sample test cases :
Input 1 :
5
2 4 6 8 10
6
Output 1 :
2
Input 2 :
9
-20 -10 -5 0 5 10 15 20 25
15
Output 2 :
6



Solution:


// You are using GCC
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    
    int n;
    cin>>n;
    
    vector<int>arr(n);
    
    for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
        cin>>arr[i];
    }
    
    int tar;
    cin>>tar;
    
    int l = 0;
    int r = n-1;
    
    while(l <= r){
        
        int mid = (l+r)/2;
        
        if(arr[mid] == tar){
            cout<<mid;
            return 0;
        }
        else if(arr[mid] < tar){
            l = mid +1;
        }
        else
        {
            r = mid -1;
        }
    }
    
    cout<<"-1";
}
